[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026836&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026836&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I would think that an "unaffiliated" home computer might fit best under .US (or
whatever country).  Seems like there should be some intermediate structure 
though.

I seem to recall Jon Postel was theorizing (a couple of years ago) about 
xxx.MARINA-DEL-REY.CA.US and the like, but I never saw any reactions to the 
idea.  One point in favor of this is that an "official" set of postal place 
names and abbreviations already exists, and the .US administrator could use 
that as a basis for evolving the structure as needed without lengthy argument 
about which would be the "best" name.  This still leaves the problem of 
multiple contenders for JONES.NEW-YORK.NY.US but at least that is not as large 
a problem as JONES.US would be.

Another way might be to hijack some existing "naming" scheme such as telephone 
numbers or social security numbers and graft it onto the domain tree.  Some 
software will be unhappy with subdomain tags that begin with numerics, but that
can be fudged...  SSN123-45-6789.US ??  It's not wonderful, but maybe about as 
good as we can expect without X.400 style naming and directory service...  
--Bill

